The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 Chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee on Friday steered clear of confirming or denying reports that he had spoken to new BCCI chief Sharad Pawar regarding Sourav Ganguly?s prospects in the Indian cricket team. Asked if he had broached the issue with Pawar, Bhattacharjee told mediapersons: ?Where do you get so much news from? It may be or it may not be.?

 He once again pretended to be hard of hearing when asked about the Election Commission wanting to implement in Bengal the ?Bihar model? of conducting polls. He smiled and said: ?I can?t hear you? At times, my ears don?t function well.?

 The Calcutta Leather Complex, in Bantala, will soon be awarded an industrial-township status and will come under the control of an Industrial Township Authority (ITA). The 14-member board of the ITA will also include representatives of tanners. 

 ommerce and industry secretary Sabyasachi Sen said around 130 acres in the 1,100-acre estate would be allotted to the IT department for setting up the Calcutta IT Park. 

 ater, the area will be converted into two Special Economic Zones, one each for leather and IT. This was decided at a meeting of the cabinet committee on industries at Writers? Buildings.

 Prasanta Pal, 24, was shot and hacked to death in Sarsuna, on the southern fringes of the city, on Thursday night. Police said Pal was attacked by a gang in Talpukur area. A man and a woman have been arrested.

 The state government will help evict about 700 people from the premises of Sreeram Jute Mills, in Metiabruz, which is closed for a long time. Home secretary Prasad Ranjan Roy said the Supreme Court had directed that the eviction be carried out by December 10. The company management has allotted three bighas nearby for rehabilitation of the evicted people, Roy said.

 A fast-track court in Baruipur, on the southern fringes of the city, has sentenced six persons to life imprisonment for murdering schoolteacher Ranjit Das. He was murdered on Kali puja night in 2003 after he had asked members of a local club not to play loudspeakers. 

 Employees of the West Bengal Pollution Control Board on Friday donated blood at its headquarters in Paribesh Bhavan to mark Bhopal Day. Minister for environment Manab Mukherjee attended the programme.

 The Bangiya Christiya Pariseba, an organisation of churches, will organise a rally in the city on December 9 to press for their demands. General secretary Herod Mullick said the members would call for the inclusion of representatives of Bengali-speaking Christians in the West Bengal Minorities? Commission.

 Tapas Das, 27, was arrested in Sodepur, on the northern fringes of the city, on Friday on charges of extortion. Police said he was caught red-handed while collecting money from a truck driver near the railway siding. He also allegedly beat up the driver, Santosh Kumar Shaw, who has been admitted to hospital.

 An entry fee of Rs 5 will be introduced at Botanical Gardens, Shibpur, on Monday. Howrah mayor Gopal Mukherjee will be the first to buy a ticket and enter the garden. 

 The Calcutta Diocese of Church of North India (CNI), which has recently opened a hospice for AIDS victims in the city, launched a programme with the state government to spread awareness on AIDS prevention on Thursday.

